8. Prohibits providing technical training or assistance related to the provision, manufacture, maintenance, or use of items listed in paragraph 7.

9. Exempts supplies and training for monitoring, verification, or peace support operations, humanitarian, human rights monitoring, and protective use.

10. Will consider modifying or terminating measures when Sudan fulfills its commitments.

11. Supports the Naivasha agreement and looks forward to its implementation.

12. Urges the international community to provide assistance to mitigate the humanitarian catastrophe in Darfur.

13. Requests the Secretary-General to activate humanitarian mechanisms and report regularly.

14. Encourages the Secretary-General's Special Representative and the independent expert to work closely together.
The Security Council:
- Extends the special political mission in Sudan for 90 days to 10 December 2004 and requests contingency planning for Darfur;
- Supports the African Union-led ceasefire commission and monitoring mission in Darfur;
- Requests the Secretary-General to assist the African Union with planning, assessments, and prepare to support implementation of a future agreement in Darfur;
- Requests the Secretary-General to report to the Security Council on progress;
- Decides to remain seized of the matter.
